    <h1>Three val&#xAD;ues sup&#xAD;port&#xAD;ing best prac&#xAD;tices in work&#xAD;place health and safety based on the WSH 2028 vi&#xAD;sion</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201109/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-09"><time>2020-11-09</time></a>
        - <span>PLACE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Health</p>
    <p>Com­pa­nies must adopt a holis­tic ap­proach, also known as To­tal WSH, to man­age safety and pro­tect health at the work­place. Ill health could re­sult in work­place ac­ci­dents, so it is cru­cial to help work­ers man­age any health con­di­tions early on.</p>
    <p>Own­er­ship</p>
    <p>Com­pa­nies need to do more than just meet reg­u­la­tory stan­dards, and should take more own­er­ship for keep­ing work­ers safe and healthy. Be­ing proac­tive such as track­ing near misses will al­low these com­pa­nies to pre­vent ac­ci­dents. The re­spon­si­bil­ity lies with ev­ery staff mem­ber to learn from these lessons, and make con­tin­ual im­prove­ments to keep the work­place safe.</p>
    <p>Tech­nol­ogy</p>
    <p>In line with the govern­ment’s plan to trans­form Sin­ga­pore into a smart na­tion, com­pa­nies are en­cour­aged to come up with in­no­va­tive so­lu­tions. For a start, they can tap on tech­nol­ogy to boost pro­duc­tiv­ity at the work­place with­out com­pro­mis­ing safety.</p>

